## Test

> Simple Model Summary

<!-- <strong style = "background: forestgreen; color: white">Correct Summary</strong> -->

```{r}
# Variables: Y = Steps; X = Heart Rate
mylm <- lm(Steps ~ HeartRate, data = health)
mylm_summary <- summary(mylm)

# > VALUES:

# 1) Estimated Y-Int
est_y_stp <- mylm_summary$coefficients["(Intercept)", "Estimate"]
est_y_stp_fmt <- round(est_y_stp, digits = 0)

# 2)
est_y_hr <- mylm_summary$coefficients["HeartRate", "Estimate"]
est_y_hr_fmt <- round(est_y_hr, digits = 0)

# 3) p-value for HeartRate
pval <- mylm_summary$coefficients["HeartRate", "Pr(>|t|)"]
pval_fmt <- formatC(pval, format = "e", digits = 2)

# 4) R^2
r_sqr <- mylm_summary$r.squared
r_sqr_fmt <- formatC(r_sqr, digits = 3)
```

<!-- Totally unneccesary, but I wanted to learn how to access the lower level elements of the linear model summary (`mylm_summary`) to use as inline R code. -->
Below we examine the summary of the simple linear regression model, where daily total steps are modeled as a function of average heart rate. The intercept (`r est_y_stp_fmt`) is not particularly meaningful in a practical sense, as it represents the predicted number of steps when heart rate is zero—a scenario that is physiologically impossible. However, the slope coefficient is both interpretable and statistically significant. Specifically, the model estimates that the average number of steps this individual takes on a day is increased by `r est_y_hr_fmt` steps for each additional beat per minute (BPM) faster in daily average heart rate. The associated p-value is extremely small ($p \approx$ `r pval_fmt`), providing strong evidence against the null hypothesis of no relationship. While the model explains a modest portion of the total variability in steps ($R^2 \approx$ `r r_sqr_fmt`), the positive association between heart rate and steps is clear and statistically meaningful.

```{r}
# Variables: Y = Steps; X = Heart Rate
pander(mylm_summary)
```

$$
\underbrace{\hat{Y}_i}_\text{Est. Total Steps} = \overbrace{`r round(mylm_summary$coef[1], 3)`}^\text{est. y-int} + \overbrace{`r round(mylm_summary$coef[2], 3)`}^\text{est. slope} \underbrace{X_i}_\text{Heart Rate}
$$

